# G-005: `err.name` is always `"Error"` for LangChain errors

## The Gotcha

LangChain's typed error classes (`AuthenticationError`, `NotFoundError`, `ContextOverflowError`, `RateLimitError`, `ServiceUnavailableError`, etc.) all extend the base `Error` class, but **do not override the `name` property** in their constructors. The expected convention — `this.name = "AuthenticationError"` — was either skipped or stripped in the build.

**Symptom**: You write a classifier like this:

```typescript
catch (err: any) {
  if (err.name === "AuthenticationError") {
    // never enters this branch — even with a provably invalid API key
  }
}
```

This silently fails. Even when `err instanceof AuthenticationError` is `true`, `err.name` is just the literal string `"Error"`.

**Verbatim evidence** (invalid API key case, from L5):
```json
{
  "constructor.name": "AuthenticationError",
  "name": "Error",
  "status": 401,
  "message": "401 {\"type\":\"error\",\"error\":{\"type\":\"authentication_error\",\"message\":\"invalid x-api-key\"}}"
}
```

Note `constructor.name` correctly reports `"AuthenticationError"`, while `name` reports the useless `"Error"`.

## The Fix

Discriminate on **`err.constructor.name`**, not `err.name`:

```typescript
try {
  await model.invoke(messages);
} catch (err: any) {
  switch (err.constructor.name) {
    case "AuthenticationError":    return { retry: false, surfaceAs: "BAD_KEY" };
    case "NotFoundError":          return { retry: false, surfaceAs: "BAD_MODEL" };
    case "ContextOverflowError":   return { retry: true,  surfaceAs: "TRIM_INPUT" };
    case "RateLimitError":         return { retry: false, surfaceAs: "RATE_LIMITED_EXCEEDED" }; // already retried internally
    case "ServiceUnavailableError":return { retry: true,  surfaceAs: "PROVIDER_5XX" };
    default:                       return { retry: false, surfaceAs: "UNKNOWN" };
  }
}
```

**Fallback** — if you're bundling and have dual instances of the error classes (so `constructor.name` gets ambiguous/duplicated across module copies), match on the message string instead:

```typescript
if (err.message.includes("authentication_error")) { /* auth failure */ }
if (err.message.includes("not_found_error"))       { /* bad model/resource */ }
if (err.message.includes("too long"))              { /* ContextOverflowError */ }
```

## Verify It Yourself

```typescript
try {
  await new ChatAnthropic({
    apiKey: "sk-ant-INVALID",
    model: "claude-haiku-4-5",
    anthropicApiUrl: "https://api.anthropic.com",   // bypass platform proxy — see G-007
  }).invoke("hi");
} catch (err: any) {
  console.log({
    "constructor.name": err.constructor.name,   // "AuthenticationError"
    "name": err.name,                            // "Error"  ← the gotcha
    "status": err.status,                        // 401
  });
}
```

## Related Notes to Watch For

- **G-006** — companion gotcha: some of these same error types have no `.status` field either, so don't assume it's always populated.
- **G-007** — using the default Anthropic base URL via a platform proxy can hide auth errors entirely (they get swallowed/transformed) — set `anthropicApiUrl` explicitly to see the real error.
- **AP-002** — the anti-pattern write-up ("catch by `err.name`") is the inverse framing of this same trap.
- **PB-004** — a full playbook for diagnosing LLM errors end-to-end if you want the broader triage flow, not just this one field.

**Bottom line**: never write `if (err.name === "SomeErrorClass")` for LangChain errors — always use `err.constructor.name`,

# G-30: `models.json` is parsed permissively — unknown fields are silently ignored at every level

## The gotcha

Pi's parser for `~/.pi/agent/models.json` is **permissive at every level** — top-level, provider-level, and model-level. If you add a field pi doesn't recognize, it is **silently dropped**: no warning, no "unknown field" error, exit code 0.

This was verified by injecting three bogus fields into a valid config:

```jsonc
{
  "junk_top_level": "Q16_TEST_JUNK_TOP",
  "providers": {
    "ollama": {
      "junk_provider_field": "Q16_TEST_JUNK_PROVIDER",
      "baseUrl": "http://localhost:11434/v1",
      "api": "openai-completions",
      "apiKey": "ollama",
      "models": [
        {
          "id": "llama3.1:8b",
          "name": "Llama 3.1 8B",
          "junk_model_field": "Q16_TEST_JUNK_MODEL"
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

Result: `exit=0`, `stderr=(empty)`, run succeeded exactly as if the junk fields were absent.

**Severity: LOW.** This is actually good news for forward-compatibility, but it's a gotcha because of the flip side (see below) — you can't rely on pi to catch typos or malformed config for you.

## What this means in practice

1. **You cannot rely on schema validation to catch typos.** Permissive parsing cuts both ways — pi can't distinguish a deliberate custom annotation from an accidental misspelling of an official key. This is the same failure mode as **G-12** (`settings.json` silently ignoring `model` instead of the correct `defaultModel`) — except here it applies to `models.json` fields too.

2. **Annotations are inert.** Fields you add survive the parse but **nothing reads them**. Pi doesn't use them for anything. If you want tooling to act on custom metadata, your own extension/script has to read the same `models.json` file independently — pi won't wire it up for you.

3. **`id` is not an alias field** (see G-13) — don't assume you can rename or annotate over `id` semantics; it's sent verbatim to the provider API.

## How to avoid getting bitten

- **Prefix all custom keys** with `_` or `x-` (e.g. `_tier`, `_role`, `_max_context`) so they're visually distinguishable from pi's official keys at a glance:

```jsonc
{
  "providers": {
    "deepseek": {
      "baseUrl": "https://api.deepseek.com/v1",
      "api": "openai-completions",
      "apiKey": "DEEPSEEK_API_KEY",
      "_tier": "hosted-cheap",
      "models": [
        {
          "id": "deepseek-chat",
          "name": "DeepSeek Chat",
          "_role": "default-hosted",
          "_max_context": 64000
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

- **Pick a distinctive prefix**, not just `_`, if you want future-proofing — a future official pi field could theoretically collide with a generic `_foo` name.
- **Don't expect pi to validate your official-key spelling.** Double-check keys like `baseUrl`, `apiKey`, `api`, `models`, `id`, `name` against docs/schema manually — a typo (`baseurl` vs `baseUrl`) will be silently ignored just like a real annotation, and you'll get a confusing runtime failure (missing provider config) rather than a parse error.
- **If you need pi to act on your annotations**, write your own extension/tooling that reads `models.json` directly — parsing succeeding does not mean pi consumes the data.

## Evidence

- Live verified: L-Research-Questions Q-16, commits `d3b23e3`/`b0fa0fd`, test file `03-pocs/L-research-questions/tests/q16-models-json-strictness.test.ts`
- Tested against `@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent@0.75.1` with Ollama `llama3.1:8b`

