## Sign in anonymously + identify the user (Supabase)

### 1. Sign in anonymously

```typescript
import { createClient } from '@supabase/supabase-js'

const supabase = createClient(process.env.SUPABASE_URL!, process.env.SUPABASE_ANON_KEY!)

const { data, error } = await supabase.auth.signInAnonymously()

if (error) throw error

const { user, session } = data
console.log(user.id)            // UUID — this is the persistent identity
console.log(user.is_anonymous)   // true
```

`signInAnonymously()` creates a real row in `auth.users` with `is_anonymous: true` and returns a full session (access_token + refresh_token), so RLS policies keyed on `auth.uid()` work immediately — no special-casing needed for anon vs named users in most policies.

### 2. Identify the user later in the session

Use `getSession()` for a cheap local check, `getUser()` when you need a server-validated identity (per the live-verified ledger behavior in [3]: `getUser()` without a session throws `AuthSessionMissingError`, status 400 — so always sign in / restore a session first):

```typescript
